TY  - JOUR
AU  - Madestam, Andreas
AU  - Shoag, Daniel
AU  - Veuger, Stan
AU  - Yanagizawa-Drott, David
T1  - Do Political Protests Matter? Evidence from the Tea Party Movement*
PY  - 2013
Y1  - 2013/11/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjt021
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 128
IS  - 4
SP  - 1633
EP  - 1685
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  -  Can protests cause political change, or are they merely symptoms of underlying shifts in policy preferences? We address this question by studying the Tea Party movement in the United States, which rose to prominence through coordinated rallies across the country on Tax Day, April 15, 2009. We exploit variation in rainfall on the day of these rallies as an exogenous source of variation in attendance. We show that good weather at this initial, coordinating event had significant consequences for the subsequent local strength of the movement, increased public support for Tea Party positions, and led to more Republican votes in the 2010 midterm elections. Policy making was also affected, as incumbents responded to large protests in their district by voting more conservatively in Congress. Our estimates suggest significant multiplier effects: an additional protester increased the number of Republican votes by a factor well above 1. Together our results show that protests can build political movements that ultimately affect policy making and that they do so by influencing political views rather than solely through the revelation of existing political preferences. 
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjt021
ER  - 



