TY  - JOUR
AU  - Ben-David, Itzhak
AU  - Graham, John R.
AU  - Harvey, Campbell R.
T1  - Managerial Miscalibration*
PY  - 2013
Y1  - 2013/11/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjt023
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 128
IS  - 4
SP  - 1547
EP  - 1584
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  -  Using a unique 10-year panel that includes more than 13,300 expected stock market return probability distributions, we find that executives are severely miscalibrated, producing distributions that are too narrow: realized market returns are within the executives’ 80% confidence intervals only 36% of the time. We show that executives reduce the lower bound of the forecast confidence interval during times of high market uncertainty; however, ex post miscalibration is worst during periods of high uncertainty. We also find that executives who are miscalibrated about the stock market show similar miscalibration regarding their own firms’ prospects. Finally, firms with miscalibrated executives seem to follow more aggressive corporate policies: investing more and using more debt financing. 
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjt023
ER  - 



